540e6754cd837ce46e7d899d.text:
Write a program that will prompt the user for a positive integer, and then produce output that looks like this:body: 0
body: 1
body: 2
 . . .
body: N-1
where N is the number the user gave.
 
For example, if the user gives number 4 as input, then the program produces 4 lines of output, with the lines numbered 0 through 3.
It's no secret you will do this with a for loop. Each time the body executes it will print out (alert) the message "body:  " followed by the appropriate
integer.  You should use the loop index variable as your body execution counter. The main issue is to get the start/stop/increment loop parameters set up 
to count properly.
Style: Use one for loop, and no other loops.

544a3ed88afe161613542b90.text:
Arrays: Organizing data 
Write a program to do the FizzBuzz problem (a former brick).  It is in the while loop section, but this time use a for loop to compute it.
Also this time, instead of printing out the numbers and "fizz" etc., put the values into an array.  Make an array of 31 items (slots 0 to 30).
Let's also just put 0 into slot 0 so we dont have to worry about if 0 is a multiple of 3 or 5.  
Then go from slot 1 on up and put either the number into the array location (if it is not a multiple
of 3 or 5), or put the appropriate "fizz", "buzz", or "fizzbuzz" into the array location.
When done, print out the 4th, 11th, 18th, and last elements (each with a separate alert).
